# Example user-crontab entry for the deploy host.  Add the line to
# `crontab -e` (no sudo — these are your own jobs).  Substitute
# <DEPLOY_PATH> and <ASSIST_THREADS_DIR> with the values from your
# .deploy.env on the dev side.
#
# Weekly threads.db retention sweep + VACUUM (Layers 0 and 1 of the
# prod growth plan, see docs/2026-05-03-prod-threads-db-growth.org
# and docs/2026-05-04-threads-db-layer-0-thread-retention.org):
#
#   0 6 * * 0 SERVICE_NAME=assist-web ASSIST_THREADS_DIR=<ASSIST_THREADS_DIR> DEPLOY_PATH=<DEPLOY_PATH> MIN_THREADS=100 /usr/bin/flock -n /tmp/assist-eval.lock <DEPLOY_PATH>/scripts/vacuum-prod-db.sh
#
# Why these arguments:
#   - `0 6 * * 0` — Sunday 06:00 local.  Clears the nightly eval
#     cron's window (23:00 + 360-min budget) with margin.
#   - Inline env (SERVICE_NAME, ASSIST_THREADS_DIR, DEPLOY_PATH,
#     MIN_THREADS) — the script refuses to start with these unset,
#     so the cron line is the single place to override.
#   - `MIN_THREADS=100` — Layer 0 retention floor: keep the 100 most-
#     recent threads, hard-delete the rest before VACUUM.  Without
#     pruning, VACUUM just rewrites the same multi-hundred-GB DB.
#   - `flock -n /tmp/assist-eval.lock` — eval cron holds this lock
#     for its whole run.  -n means "skip if held"; never let the
#     sweep+VACUUM race the eval.  The script also takes a separate
#     flock on $threads_db.lock to serialize against `make vacuum-now`.
#   - Absolute paths only — cron has no PATH context.
